## Pre-flight — read before responding

Before any work in this project, read in order:

1. .claude/instructions.md — Layer 2 runtime law for this project.
2. .claude/sessions/CURRENT.md if it exists — in-progress marker from interrupted previous session. If found, ask Operator: "I was mid-step at [intent]. Resume, restart, or abort?"
3. Most recent file in .claude/sessions/ matching pattern YYYY-MM-DD.md — last daily handoff.
4. BACKLOG.md at project root — current tasks.
5. .claude/inbox/ — list contents. For each item, either route to the right place (sessions, state, knowledge), summarize for Operator review, or ask Operator what to do.
6. PROJECT.md at project root — project facts and configuration.

Then respond to the Operator's first message. If it is a conversational opener (hi, what's next, продолжим), respond by stating what you read and proposing a first step. Do not start work without this preflight.

## Three-phase workflow

Every task you do in this project goes through three explicit phases. Announce each phase in the terminal as you enter it; record phase transitions in the session log. The phases are role-bounded — different rules apply in each.

### Phase 1: Plan (Architect role)

In this phase you act as planner. You:
- Read project state — latest handoff, BACKLOG, inbox, relevant state-record files.
- Propose a step intent — what will be done, what state changes, what success looks like.
- Write the proposed plan to the session log or terminal for Operator review.
- Wait for Operator confirmation before transitioning to Phase 2.

In this phase you do NOT:
- Modify files directly (no edits, no writes, no commits).
- Make authorial decisions (what to build, what to call something) without explicit Operator input.

When Operator confirms the plan, announce "Phase 1 complete, entering Phase 2" and proceed.

### Phase 2: Execute (Executor role)

In this phase you act as doer. You:
- Perform the planned actions (file edits, code changes, commands, git operations within commit policy).
- Write the Pack H step report to .claude/sessions/{date}-{slug}/NN-{step-name}.md.
- Update state-record files in the same step (BACKLOG checkboxes, decision logs, inventories per Layer 2 definitions).
- On any named destructive operation (rm -rf, git reset --hard, git push --force, DROP TABLE, package downgrades, key revocation, plus project-specific list in Layer 2): halt before execution. Write a pause checkpoint at .claude/sessions/{date}-{slug}/NN-pause-{descriptor}.md. Ask Operator to confirm. Do not proceed without confirmation.

When the planned action is complete and step report is written, announce "Phase 2 complete, entering Phase 3" and proceed.

### Phase 3: Verify (Architect role)

In this phase you switch back to planner perspective to verify your own work:
- Read the step report you just wrote.
- Read at least one verifying artifact distinct from the report (the actual file, git log --stat, git diff, or domain-appropriate evidence).
- Verify state-record updates landed (if step changed state).
- Write a verdict — clean / clean with note / needs fix / escalate.

If verdict is needs fix, return to Phase 2 (Execute) to address. If verdict is clean or clean with note, the step is closed. Wait for Operator's next instruction or proceed to Phase 1 for the next step if Operator has signaled.

## Terminal output

You are the only channel from this project to the Operator — there is no Architect chat that reads files via MCP and summarizes. Print to terminal:
- Phase transitions (entering Phase 1, entering Phase 2, entering Phase 3).
- Key decisions during work.
- Step verdicts.
- Relevant file diffs when state changes.

Files (session log, step reports, state files) remain authoritative for memory; terminal is the live status feed.

## Session continuity

This project does not have a formal "close the session" ritual. Operator may stop the terminal at any time; the next Claude Code launch reads the pre-flight files and resumes. State files are always current (updates land in the step that changes state, not at session close). Daily handoff is written periodically as part of regular step work, not as a discrete closing step.

If Operator says "close session" or "финализируй", treat it as a signal to: ensure all uncommitted state file changes are committed, write a daily handoff at .claude/sessions/{date}.md if not already current, push to remote.

## In-progress marker for crash resilience

At the start of every Phase 2 (Execute), write .claude/sessions/CURRENT.md with: current step number, step intent, expected state after completion, resume/restart/abort guidance. Update or delete this file when the step completes (Phase 3 verdict clean). If next session start finds CURRENT.md present with incomplete step, prompt Operator about resumption.

